
I'd try something like this:

int i = 1;
while (i < n && a[i] == a[i-1]) {
    ++i;
}

if (i == n) {
    return 0;
}

int j = n-2;
while (j >= 0 && a[j] == a[j+1]) {
    --j;
}

int right_only = a[i-1] * (n-i);
int left_only = a[j+1] * (j+1);

int ans = min(left_only, right_only);
for (int k = i; k <= j; ++k) {
    ans = min(ans, a[k] * k + a[k] * (n-k-1));
}

Firstly sweep from the left and try to find a prefix of equal values, then the last value
in the prefix will only need a right operations, then do the same from right to left and check for a left only operation.
The remaining values in the middle will be forced to used 2 operations.

You are given an array arr of length n. You can do the following operations any number of times (possible zero):
- choose an index i with 1 <= i <= n - 1 and set all position 0, 1, ... i - 1 to arr[i]; this costs i * arr[i].
- choose an index i with 0 <= i <= n - 2 and set all positions i+1, i+2, ..., n - 1 to arr[i]; this costs (n - i - 1) * arr[i].
Compute the minimum total cost to make all elements equal.
